<p>hmmm, you're right. Radius limit would be a big nerf. I retract the suggestion.</p>
<p>But what I meant by &quot;true nature&quot; was its defining characteristic, that it is not what it appears to be. For example, the gaurd outside the door may know that there is an elephant in the room, but as long as he thinks it is <em>just</em> an elephant, there is no shift. But if he starts to get a clue that it might be something more than just a pacyderm, a shift is triggered. And if he deduces, perhaps by being a long-term gaurd, that 964 is something that changes, shifting would accelerate in direct proportion to his certainty. Which, now that I think about it, implies a positive-feedback loop and a source of constant containment breach threat.</p>

